Setup:
  (Follows the procedure in PowerTap Pro Emulator Installation Guide,
   Chapter 4: Setting up Stand-Alone PC Ethernet)
- Configure the PC ethernet port:
  Go to Local Area Connection Properties, turn off all components
  other than Internet Protocol
  In Internet Protocol Properties, select to use the following static
  IP address:  192.168.1.1, and subnet mask: 255.255.255.0 
- Go to C:\WINNT\system32\drivers\etc, edit the file hosts with NotePad to add:
  (p. 4-9)
  192.168.1.1	tap_nic
  192.168.12	powertap
- Connect the serial port on the PowerTap Pro to a PC serial port using the
  provided cable and serial port adaptor.  Configurate serial port according
  to the manual p. 4-11.  Type in the commands in p. 4-12.
  (Suggest to use Reflection X VT (Reflection for UNIX and Digital) instead of
   Hyper Terminal.  To use, start the program, select
   Connection | Connection setup, click Serial port, More Settings)
- Check the PowerTap Pro setup by connecting the PC ethernet port to the
  PowerTap Pro ethernet port using a CROSSOVER cable.  Ping the powertap
  IP (192.168.1.2) to see if there is any response.


Correct procedure to boot up the evaluation board:
- Connect power cable to eval board, and the CPU fan.
  (Currently we use a PC power supply to give power to the board.  In order for
  the board to be stable, we need to use the 2 CD-ROM drives from the PC to
  load the power supply.)
- Connect PowerTap Pro cable to the eval board CORRECTLY. (Port is on the CPU
  daughter board.)  Pin 1 (red cable) should connect to pin 1 on the board.
  CAUTION: Make sure connect is correct.  Otherwise PowerTap Pro can be damaged!
- Power up the eval board first. (Turn on power supply, as well as the
  power toggle switch on eval board.)  PPC will boot from DINK32 on flash.
  (Make sure Code Warrior is set up so there will be no reset on launch.)
- Wait until all 4 debug LEDs on eval board are off.
  If anyone of them is on or flashing, press reset again.
- Power up the PowerTap Pro.  Make sure HeartBeat LED is blinking green
  (Blinking red means problems).


Code Warrior
Setup:
- Go to Edit | Preferences | Debugger | Remote Connections, add a new
  connection for PowerTap Pro.  Choose TCP/IP connection type,
  Debugger: EPPC - AMC PowerTap Pro. Hostname same as in host.
  Interface Clock freq 32 MHz.
- To create a new project, Go to File | New | Project | EPPC Stationery Wizard,
  Select Generic boards, and PowerPC 7455 Processors.  Select the connection
  you created for PowerTap Pro.  This will create a .mcp project file.
- Go to Debug Version Settings, check Linker | EPPC Linker on address settings,
  and Code Generation | Global Optimizations setting.

To run Code Warrior, a current license.dat file is needed on the
CodeWarrior program directory.  Obtain one from Bob of Motorola.


PowerTap Pro LED:
- HeartBeat LED should be blinking green in normal condition
- TGT PWR should be green if the eval board is powered
- RUN/PAUSE indicates whether the target board is running (green)
  or paused (red).

If you see the following error message when trying to run at debug mode:
  AMCProtocolPlugin: Invalid rocessor specified
then check the Debugger:Remote Debugging: Connection Setting and make sure
the right connection (PowerTap) is used.


Marvell Eval Board Info
-----------------------

The board has 128 MByte RAM, starting from 0.  However, the first 1M is not
usable.  Hence make sure all addresses (code, data, stack) is above 0x00100000.

To find out CPU/Bus info, connect the serial port on eval board to a PC serial
board.  DINK32 will print out information on reset.  Need to find out serial
port configuration from Eddy.

CPU clock: 864 MHz
Bus clock: 133 MHz

Notice regular serial cable should be used.  I tried using RJ11 with adaptors,
but it does not work.  Also use Reflexion instead of Hyperterminal.
The serial port on my Labtop docking system is COM2.  The serial porting
setting is: 115200 baud, 8 bit, no parity, no hardware flow control on transmit
and receive, 0 delays.  (The file Marvell.r2w has been set up for the correct
serial port setting.)

For benchmarking using TBH and TBL registers:
- Turn on TBEN bits in HID2 register to use TBH and TBL.
- 1 TB count corresponds to 4 bus transactions.  Hence
  CPU cycle = TB count * 4 * 864/133 = TB count * 26

Use
  #progma optimization_level n
  #progma scheduler on/off
to overwrite code generation optimization level



